  <p>From a longevity perspective, the critical insight is that the standard "no CKD" classification (eGFR above 60) includes a wide range of kidney health. An eGFR of 62 and an eGFR of 110 are both technically "normal" &#8212; but the cardiovascular and mortality risk profiles are dramatically different. This is why the longevity-optimal target is above 90, not simply above 60.</p>

  <p>More important than any single value is the trajectory. A five-year decline from eGFR 98 to 85 &#8212; both technically "normal" &#8212; represents a rate of loss (-2.6 mL/min/year) that, if sustained, will reach CKD stage 2 within two decades. The normal age-related decline is roughly 1 mL/min/year after age 40 &#8212; faster decline demands investigation of modifiable causes.</p>
</section>

